SIMPLE: inwardness
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Inwardness
<hw>In"ward*ness</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Internal or true
state; essential nature; <as>as, the <ex>inwardness</ex> of
conduct</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sense can not arrive to the <qex>inwardness</qex>⟦br⟧
Of things.</q> <rj><qau>Dr. H. More.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Intimacy; familiarity.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Heartiness; earnestness.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What was wanted was more <qex>inwardness</qex>, more feeling.</q>
<rj><qau>M. Arnold.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Inwards</ent>⟦br⟧
